		<description><![CDATA[What causes glaucoma? Unfortunately, currently no known cause nor is there any way to prevent its occurrence. What is known is that some people are more likely to have it than others. Among them: - Diabetics - Those with a significant injury to the eye. - People who use steroids. - Those with relatively thin [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img src="http://www.glaucoma.org/assets_c/2011/03/eye_test_closeup-440-thumb-440xauto-274.jpg" alt="Causes of Glaucoma" align="right" style="padding-left:5px" width="200"/>What causes glaucoma? Unfortunately, currently no known cause nor is there any way to prevent its occurrence. What is known is that some people are more likely to have it than others. Among them:</p>
<p>- Diabetics<br />
- Those with a significant injury to the eye.<br />
- People who use steroids.<br />
- Those with relatively thin corneas.<br />
- Those with myopia<br />
- Women, African Americans, the elderly and those with family history of glaucoma.<span id="more-1363"></span></p>
<p>If you have been diagnosed with glaucoma, be sure to go regularly to the ophthalmologist to make you all the necessary studies and follows exactly the treatment that you have specified. Many people do not follow the treatment because they feel good and do not realize that they lose sight gradually. With proper medication, it is possible to stop this progress and keep a good look longer.</p>
<p>And whatever your situation, do not forget to make some kind of physical activity. According to researchers, this is the first time a study shows the association between exercise and eye pressure (other previous research examined the effect of physical activity on the two components of the pressure in the eye: intraocular pressure and blood pressure), and the results appear promising. Take action to feel better and look better!</p>
