		<title>Exercise helps reduce the risk of developing glaucoma</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/RadioStorytime/~3/iJCEr9S7Li0/</link>
		<comments>http://www.radiostorytime.com/health-care/exercise-helps-reduce-the-risk-of-developing-glaucoma/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 19 May 2012 06:00:37 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>mzPOTTER</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Fitness]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Health Care]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Exercise]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Exercise helps reduce the risk of developing glaucoma]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[glaucoma]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.radiostorytime.com/?p=1362</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The list of benefits that exercise brings something else to add: reduce the risk of developing glaucoma. A recent study found that keep moving could help keep in check the development of this condition that affects the eyes and one of the leading causes of blindness. In this article we tell you more details on [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img src="http://c713371.r71.cf2.rackcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/iStock_000016584209XSmall_Alexander-Raths.jpg" alt="Exercise helps reduce the risk of developing glaucoma" align="left" style="padding-right:5px" width="200"/>The list of benefits that exercise brings something else to add: reduce the risk of developing glaucoma. A recent study found that keep moving could help keep in check the development of this condition that affects the eyes and one of the leading causes of blindness. In this article we tell you more details on these findings and other things you can do to protect the health of your eyes.</p>
<p>Glaucoma is the second leading cause of blindness in the world and, according to World Health Organization (WHO) estimates that by 2020 there will be 80 million people with glaucoma. That is one of the main concerns about the health of eyes.</p>
<p>In search of new data on a group of researchers from the Institute of Ophthalmology at University College London in England, found that physical activity may help protect the eyes of glaucoma.<span id="more-1362"></span></p>
<p>To reach these results, which were published in the journal Investigative Ophthalmology &#038; Visual Science, experts looked at the relationship between physical activity and eye pressure in 5,650 men and women between 48 and 90 years of age in Britain.</p>
<p>According to information provided by participants about their physical activity at work and in his spare time, they were described as inactive, moderately inactive, moderately active or active. The pressure in the eye of the members of each group was controlled according to its variation with the passage of time were evaluated between 1993 and 1997, first, and then between 2006 and 2010.</p>
<p>Thus, researchers found that those who performed moderate exercise for about fifteen years, were 25 percent less likely to have high eye pressure. This is important because the eye pressure is one of the main risk factors for glaucoma.</p>
<p>Glaucoma causes progressive damage to the optic nerve and causes loss of vision because the optic nerve is responsible for transmitting visual signals from eye to brain. The most common form of glaucoma, known as primary open angle glaucoma is associated with increased fluid pressure within the eye, when the pressure is too high for the optic nerve.</p>
<p>This does not mean that everyone with high blood pressure in one eye or both develop the disease. Similarly, the damage to the eye related to glaucoma can occur even when the pressure in the eye is normal, and worst of all is that most people know they have this condition because it causes no symptoms. It is therefore important to see an ophthalmologist, who is the specialist who deals with the health of the eyes, at least once a year.</p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/RadioStorytime/~4/iJCEr9S7Li0" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
