		<title>Yoga can help with chronic low back pain</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/RadioStorytime/~3/wQFLbT_VSpY/</link>
		<comments>http://www.radiostorytime.com/fitness-2/yoga-can-help-with-chronic-low-back-pain/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 12 May 2012 06:00:34 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>mzPOTTER</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Fitness]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[back pain]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[yoga]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Yoga can help with chronic low back pain]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.radiostorytime.com/?p=1358</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[A recent study suggests that yoga may be more beneficial for patients with chronic low back pain than standard treatment. Yoga is an ancient system of exercise, healing and relaxation. Yoga has been the subject of many scientific studies that have suggested various psychological and physical theories. In research done in humans has shown that [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img style="padding-right: 5px;" src="http://c713371.r71.cf2.rackcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/iStock_000009772854XSmall_Artur-Bogacki.jpg" alt="Yoga can help with chronic low back pain" width="200" align="left" />A recent study suggests that yoga may be more beneficial for patients with chronic low back pain than standard treatment.</p>
<p>Yoga is an ancient system of exercise, healing and relaxation. Yoga has been the subject of many scientific studies that have suggested various psychological and physical theories. In research done in humans has shown that yoga reduces heart rate and blood pressure, increases lung capacity and time during which you can hold your breath, muscle relaxation and improved body composition, cause weight loss and increase overall physical endurance. Preliminary research suggests that yoga may reduce chronic back pain, but more research is needed before drawing definitive conclusions.<span id="more-1358"></span></p>
<p>In a new study, researchers randomly assigned (by chance) to 313 adults with chronic low back pain to a 12 yoga classes for 3 months or standard care (or usual). To determine the outcome of the questionnaire responses were included Roland-Morris Disability (RMDG), measurements of pain and general health measures after three months and again at six and 12 months follow up.</p>
<p>The researchers found that patients in the yoga group had greater improvement in the functioning of the back than the standard care group. In addition, scores were averaged RMDG 2.17, 1.48 and 1.57 points lower for patients of yoga in three, six and 12 months respectively.</p>
<p>The authors noted that two patients in the standard care group and 12 in the yoga group reported increased pain and other adverse effects. In addition, missing data of 21 patients in the yoga group and 18 in the usual care group.</p>
<p>The authors concluded that yoga can be more beneficial than standard care for patients with chronic low back pain, however, due to limitations of the study, more research is needed before firm conclusions can be drawn.</p>
