<p>- Particularly for men, plates or lizards (push ups): Aim to do 3 sets of 12 to 15 repetitions each. This is a classic exercise that will strengthen your arms, torso and abdomen. If you can not perform all the series, never mind. Begins with a minimal amount. You will gain in strength and endurance over time.</p>
<p>- For both sexes, the abdominals. A flat stomach is not the only advantage derived, since men and women see an improvement in the stability and strength to keep the positions and stronger backs. Men in particular will also achieve a better push during penetration. Lie on the floor with your legs bent and arms bent behind his head. Rest your head on your hands, chin toward the ceiling. Now, move the torso up without raising the hips off the floor, abdominal muscles tight (try not to push your head with your arms to avoid injury to the neck). Do 3 sets of 15 repetitions each. To avoid back pain, you can work your abdominal muscles up. Stand with legs slightly apart, the muscles of the abdomen compressed, pulling your navel inward. Lift one knee while trying to play with the opposite hand. Repeated for the other side. You can switch to lift the knee once (single), or double or triple it, leaning heavily on the opposite leg.<span id="more-1354"></span></p>
<p>- Hip lifts (also known as a bridge or bridge): the two partners can strengthen the buttocks, pelvis, lower back and the back of the thighs. Lie down on a mattress on the floor, bend your legs and place your heels near the buttocks. Now, raise your hips, glutes contracted (abs tight, trying to get the belly down) and hold the position for 3 to 4 seconds. Lower hips to floor and repeat. As a goal, intend to make 3 sets of 15 repetitions each. These exercises strengthen the pelvic muscles which helps to intensify the contractions during orgasm.</p>
<p>- Squats: Stand with legs slightly apart, arms along the body (you can do them with weights or without them). Bend your knees, bringing the pelvis back (as if you were to sit in an imaginary chair). Returns to the starting position and repeat. You can perform them with legs apart or together. Avoid tilting the torso forward. All movement is done with the hip, bringing back as you bend your knees. With this exercise you strengthen the buttocks and thighs, giving you more thrust at the hip, more strength and more strength to play other positions in the sexual encounter. Perform 3 sets of 8 to 12 repetitions each.</p>
<p>Another alternative that can also be very useful are called Kegel exercises, which are recommended to control urinary incontinence (when you can not stand the urge or desire to urinate or when you get a bit of urine when laughing or sneezing , for example). While these exercises are geared primarily to women (especially after childbirth), men also benefit because they can control ejaculation and to increase the volume of blood in the penis to achieve harder erections.</p>
<p>How are Kegel exercises? It is easy to learn this technique, but can sometimes be difficult to identify the supporting muscles located in the pelvis, and consciously not used frequently. One way to detect them is trying to stop urine while going out. If you do, you learn the basic movement. Once you&#8217;ve identified the muscles, contrÃ¡elos and hold the position for 3 seconds, then relax for 3 seconds and repeat this sequence 10 times, three or four times a day.</p>
